result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Xou Thao

records.addlTxt: 01:54 PM  Attorney Jon D. Seifert appeared by phone means for Plaintiff State of Wisconsin. Defendant Xou Thao failed to appear Hmong Interpreter, Tou Ja-Vue Yang appeared by video means.  Interpreter sworn.  Interpreter attempts to make contact with a defendant Xou Thao if on the call. No response. Court requests Interpreter interpret Mr. Thao to unmute if on the call.  No response.  Court asks Mr. Interpreter to interpret the following:  A criminal complaint issued against Xou Thao alleging possession of drug paraphernalia as a PTC as a repeater.  A summons was issued to Xou Thao to appear in court today at 1:30.  He fails to appear and fails to provide any reason for his FTA.  Mr. Seifert requests a warrant.  Court authorizes for Xou Thao for failure to appear pursuant to summons.
